    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>What Proofing Means in Distilling</h2>
      <p>
        Proofing is the final step before bottling a spirit. Most spirits leave the still at very high alcohol content, ranging from 130 proof for traditional pot still whiskey to nearly 190 proof for vodka and neutral spirits made on a continuous column still. Almost no consumer spirits are bottled at still strength because the high alcohol content is harsh, expensive in tax, and difficult to drink. The distiller dilutes the high-proof distillate down to the final bottling strength, typically 80 proof (40 percent ABV) for most vodkas and gins, 80 to 100 proof for whiskey, and 80 proof for most rum. Some craft spirits and barrel-strength offerings are bottled at higher proof for connoisseurs. Note that producing spirits at home may be illegal in your jurisdiction — in the United States it requires a federal TTB Distilled Spirits Plant permit, and many other countries restrict or prohibit unlicensed distillation, so always check your local laws first.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>The Dilution Equation</h2>
      <p>
        The math is simple: a fixed amount of pure alcohol takes up a smaller percentage of a bigger total volume. If you have 10 liters of 75 percent ABV spirit (which contains 7.5 liters of pure ethanol), and you want to dilute it to 40 percent ABV, the final volume needs to be 7.5 divided by 0.40, or 18.75 liters. The water to add is the final volume minus the starting volume, in this case 8.75 liters. The general equation is final volume equals starting volume times starting ABV divided by target ABV. The Pearson square is a graphical shortcut to the same answer and is sometimes preferred when blending two spirits of different proofs.
      </p>

      <h2>Why Volume-Based Math Is Approximate</h2>
      <p>
        When ethanol and water mix, the total volume contracts slightly because the polar water molecules pack more tightly into the gaps between ethanol molecules than they do alone. At common bottling proofs the contraction is about 2 to 3 percent of the calculated total volume. This calculator returns a volume-based dilution and ignores contraction, which is accurate enough for planning purposes. Licensed distillers are required to verify the actual bottled proof with a TTB-approved alcoholometer or hydrometer immediately before bottling because the legal label proof must match the measured value within 0.15 percent ABV.
      </p>

      <h2>Practical Proofing Tips</h2>
      <p>
        Always use distilled, deionized, or reverse-osmosis water for proofing. Tap and well water contain minerals, chlorine, and dissolved gases that can cause louching (a cloudy haze in clear spirits), discoloration in aged spirits, and unpleasant flavors that no amount of filtration can fully remove. Add water slowly while stirring gently to avoid heat shock, and let the proofed spirit rest for 24 hours before final measurement because the contraction takes time to complete. For barrel-aged spirits, taste at multiple proof points before deciding on a final bottling strength because aroma compounds change perception dramatically as the alcohol level drops.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What does proof mean?</h3>
      <p>
        US proof equals two times the ABV percentage. An 80 proof spirit is 40 percent ABV.
      </p>

      <h3>What formula does this calculator use?</h3>
      <p>
        Final volume equals starting volume times starting ABV divided by target ABV. Water to add is final volume minus starting volume.
      </p>

      <h3>Does it account for ethanol-water contraction?</h3>
      <p>
        No. The calculator returns a volume-based dilution that ignores the 2 to 3 percent contraction. Always verify the final proof with a calibrated alcoholometer.
      </p>

      <h3>What water should I use for proofing?</h3>
      <p>
        Always use distilled, deionized, or reverse-osmosis water. Tap water can cause louching, discoloration, and off-flavors.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I use this for blending two spirits?</h3>
      <p>
        For two-spirit blending, use the Pearson square or solve V1*A1 + V2*A2 = (V1+V2)*A_target. This calculator is for diluting one spirit with water only.
      </p>

